{"key":"processedPost-9499828","value":{"id":9499828,"first":9499529,"last":9500298,"when":1230356225,"utime":"12/27/08 07:37 AM","cleanedPost":"Knock it the fuck off with the arguments.<br />You should always vent steam for several minutes before placing the weight on a pressure cooker, or closing the toggle valve on sterilizers.<br />The reason is basic physics.&nbsp; As the water 'begins' to boil in a closed container, pressure will be created by expansion.&nbsp; It's not steam pressure, but air pressure.&nbsp; Once the pressure is reached and steam begins to vent from the weight, it will eventually come up to where 15psi equals 250F, but it takes quite a bit of time.&nbsp; Since we're timing for sterilization, we want the 250F figure to be reached the whole time we're at 15 psi.<br />I ran a series of tests a few years ago with an infrared thermometer, and it takes an extra fifteen to twenty minutes after fifteen psi is reached for the external surfaces of the PC to stabilize at maximum temp if steam is not vented first. If steam is vented for a few minutes, maximum surface temperature is reached as 15 psi is reached. That's the reason to always do it.<br />RR"}}